# dpm-api Access — Server Proxy Only

`lib/api.ts` is `server-only`. **Never** import it (or call dpm-api URLs) from `"use client"` components or any code that runs in the browser.

## Rule

| Context | Allowed |
|---------|---------|
| Server component (`page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, no `"use client"`) | ✅ `import { manual } from "@/lib/api"` |
| `lib/*.ts` with `import "server-only"` at the top | ✅ |
| Next.js API route (`app/api/**/route.ts`) | ✅ proxy layer |
| `"use client"` component | ❌ never — call the Next.js API route instead |

## Pattern

```ts
// ✅ server component / server-only lib — direct call
import { manual } from "@/lib/api";
const market = await manual.getMarketStatus(external_id);

// ✅ client component — call the Next.js proxy route
const res = await fetch(`/api/dpm/markets/${id}/activate`, { method: "POST" });

// ❌ never do this in a "use client" file
import { manual } from "@/lib/api";   // will throw at runtime
fetch(process.env.DPM_API_URL + "/markets/...");  // exposes internal URL + key
```

## Adding a new dpm-api action

1. Create `app/api/dpm/<resource>/<action>/route.ts` — call `manual.*` there.
2. Call `fetch("/api/dpm/...")` from the client component.
3. Never pass `DPM_API_URL` or `DPM_API_KEY` to the browser.
